  &lt;Comment&gt;
    &lt;Title&gt;Ward 5. Needs better management.&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Anonymous&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;Got on the ward 5 for 11am. Waited for 2.5hrs for a bed. Watching the staff was eye opening. Lots of staff but not working together. There was a male nurse who I think was a charge nurse who was abrupt and rude to patients. Staff didn't know which patient was which. There appeared to be a lot of confusion between the staff.The senior nurses appeared more interested in the computers than the actual patients. Nurses walked past patients vomiting and ignored them. Patient care was poor and evident. I say this as a nurse myself whom has been qualified for 25 years. This is the 2nd time I have been unfortunate enough to be on this awful ward. I have been a patient on other wards at BRI where the staff have been amazing. I used to work at BRI myself.When I returned to the ward, having had surgery to my bowel, no-one checked my obs more than once. I'd had a GA too. No-one came to ask if I would like a drink or food (had fasted by this point for 22hrs). I had to ask them for a drink and food. No-one asked if I'd passed urine (integral part of recovering from a GA). Management needs to get to grips with this ward. The staff don't make eye contact in fear if being asked to do something. It feels like being a conveyor belt. Staff need to learn inter personal skills and communicate as there is a lack of this.&lt;/CommentText&gt;
